83rd OREGON LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY--2026 Regular Session
B-Engrossed
House Bill 4132
Ordered by the House February 27
Including House Amendments dated February 16 and February 27
Sponsored by Representatives EVANS, BOWMAN, HELFRICH, PHAM H, Senators MANNING JR, SMITH DB;
Representatives ANDERSEN, BUNCH, CHAICHI, DOBSON, GOMBERG, GRAYBER, ISADORE, JAVADI,
LEVY B, LEWIS, MCDONALD, MUNOZ, NELSON, NGUYEN D, OWENS, RIEKE SMITH, RUIZ, WISE (Pre-
session filed.)
SUMMARY
The following summary is not prepared by the sponsors of the measure and is not a part of the body thereof subject
to consideration by the Legislative Assembly. It is an editor’s brief statement of the essential features of the
measure. The statement includes a measure digest written in compliance with applicable readability standards.
Digest: Makes changes to veteran laws. (Flesch Readability Score: 66.4).
[Declares that it is the goal of the Legislative Assembly to fund the Department of Veterans’ Af-
fairs in an amount that is not less than $10,000,000, from the General Fund, in 2015 dollars, adjusted
for inflation.]
[Requires the Director of Veterans’ Affairs to add additional full-time positions within the depart-
ment. Creates in the department the position of Veterans Employment Coordinator.]
Requires the director to be a veteran who has received a discharge or release under other than
dishonorable conditions. Allows the director to appoint a deputy director, subject to approval by
the Governor.
Directs the department to develop and implement a grant program for suicide prevention and
workforce training and preparation. Allows moneys in the Veterans’ Services Fund to be used for
the grant program. Increases an expenditure limitation for the purpose of the grant program.
Directs the director to distribute moneys appropriated for county veterans’ service officer pro-
grams on a quarterly basis. Directs the department to provide a report on the quarterly distribution
process.
Changes who are allowed to request county veteran discharge records.
Increases, from $5,000 to $10,000, the cap on the individual grant amount that is allowed under
the Veteran Educational Bridge Grant Program.
Directs the Judicial Department, in consultation with the Oregon Criminal Justice Commission,
to study methods for providing access to veterans’ treatment courts to residents of each county or
judicial district.
Takes effect on July 1, 2026.
1 A BILL FOR AN ACT
2 Relating to veterans; creating new provisions; amending ORS 192.390, 406.020, 406.462, 408.115 and
3 408.425; and prescribing an effective date.
4 Be It Enacted by the People of the State of Oregon:
5 SECTION 1. This 2026 Act shall be known and may be cited as the 2026 Oregon Veterans’
6 Services Supplemental Investments Initiative.
7
8 DIRECTOR AND DEPUTY DIRECTOR
9
10 SECTION 2. ORS 406.020 is amended to read:
11 406.020. The Department of Veterans’ Affairs shall be under the supervision and control of the
12 Director of Veterans’ Affairs. The Governor shall appoint the director subject to confirmation by
13 the Senate in the manner provided in ORS 171.562 and 171.565. The appointment may not be made
14 without the written approval of the Advisory Committee provided for in ORS 406.210. The director
NOTE: Matter in boldfaced type in an amended section is new; matter [italic and bracketed] is existing law to be omitted.
New sections are in boldfaced type.
LC 157

B-Eng. HB 4132
1 shall be a veteran[,] who received a discharge or release under other than dishonorable con-
2 ditions, chosen on the basis of executive and administrative ability.
3 SECTION 3. The Director of Veterans’ Affairs, subject to approval by the Governor, may
4 appoint a deputy director. In appointing a deputy director, the director shall consider the
5 experience that a veteran may bring if a veteran is appointed to the position. The deputy
6 director serves at the pleasure of the director, has full authority to act for the director and
7 is subject to the control of the director.
8
9 VETERANS SUICIDE PREVENTION GRANT PROGRAM
10
11 SECTION 4. (1) As used in this section, “veteran” has the meaning given that term in
12 ORS 408.225. “Veteran” includes a disabled veteran as defined in ORS 408.225.
13 (2) The Department of Veterans’ Affairs shall develop and implement a grant program
14 for veteran suicide prevention and workforce training and preparation. The purpose of the
15 grant program is to help veterans with suicide prevention and transition to the workforce
16 and business community.
17 (3) Under the grant program, the department shall award grants through a request for
18 proposal process to entities involved in pairing suicide prevention with workforce training
19 and preparation.
20 (4) The department shall:
21 (a) Develop criteria for entities that provide programs for suicide prevention and
22 workforce training and preparation;
23 (b) By rule, establish processes and procedures for veterans to apply for assistance from
24 entities that are awarded a grant under the grant program; and
25 (c) Prioritize awarding grants to entities that provide opportunities for veterans to par-
26 ticipate in the veterans’ local communities.
27 (5) The department may solicit and accept gifts, grants and donations from public and
28 private sources to further the purposes of this section.
29 (6) The department may use moneys in the Veterans’ Services Fund established pursuant
30 to Article XV, section 4f, of the Oregon Constitution, to develop, implement and maintain the
31 grant program.
32 (7) The department may adopt rules to implement the provisions of this section.
33 SECTION 5. (1) Not later than January 2, 2029, the Department of Veterans’ Affairs shall
34 prepare and submit a report to the interim committees of the Legislative Assembly related
35 to veterans on the status of the grant program developed and implemented under section 4
36 of this 2026 Act.
37 (2) The department shall use moneys in the Veterans’ Services Fund established pursuant
38 to Article XV, section 4f, of the Oregon Constitution, for the initial moneys used to develop,
39 implement and maintain the grant program under section 4 of this 2026 Act.
40
41 COUNTY VETERANS’ SERVICE OFFICER PROGRAM
42
43 SECTION 6. ORS 406.462 is amended to read:
44 406.462. (1) Moneys appropriated to the Director of Veterans’ Affairs for the purposes described
45 in ORS 406.450 must be distributed to county governing bodies and expended for the purposes of
[2]

B-Eng. HB 4132
1 ORS 406.450 and may not be used to supplant moneys currently budgeted by the director for services
2 provided by county veterans’ service officers.
3 (2) The director shall distribute moneys appropriated to the director for the purposes
4 described in ORS 406.450 on a quarterly basis as follows:
5 (a) Each fiscal year, the director shall notify each county governing body of the amount
6 of moneys to be distributed to the county governing body for the fiscal year.
7 (b) The county governing body shall provide the director a copy of the county’s budget
8 for the services to be provided by the county veterans’ service officer for the fiscal year.
9 (c) At the end of each calendar quarter, the county governing body shall provide the di-
10 rector a report on the moneys the county expended during the calendar quarter for the
11 services provided by the county veterans’ service officer.
12 (d) Upon receipt of the county governing body’s quarterly report, the director shall dis-
13 tribute to the county governing body a portion of moneys allocated to the county governing
14 body in an amount that is based on the proportion of all moneys budgeted for all services
15 provided by county veterans’ service officers that were expended during the calendar quar-
16 ter.
17 (e) At the end of each calendar quarter, the county governing body may also provide the
18 director documentation for moneys the county expended during a previous calendar quarter
19 in the fiscal year for the services provided by the county veterans’ service officer that the
20 county had not previously reported to the director and for which the county governing body
21 has not received a distribution of moneys from the director. Upon receipt of the documen-
22 tation, the director shall distribute to the county governing body a portion of moneys allo-
23 cated to the county governing body in an amount that is based on the proportion of all
24 moneys budgeted for all services provided by county veterans’ service officers that were ex-
25 pended during the calendar quarter within which the county expended the moneys for which
26 the county governing body provided the director documentation.
27 (3) At the end of each fiscal year, the director shall calculate the remaining moneys not
28 distributed during the fiscal year and distribute the remaining moneys using a formula es-
29 tablished under ORS 406.454 to each county governing body that expended 90 percent or more
30 of the moneys that the county budgeted for services provided by the county veterans’ service
31 officer for the fiscal year as specified under subsection (2)(b) of this section. The director
32 shall distribute the remaining moneys within 90 days from the last date of the fiscal year.
33 [(2)] (4) Notwithstanding subsection (1) of this section, the director may reduce the amount of
34 moneys distributed to county governing bodies for county veterans’ service officers if there is a de-
35 crease in the amount of General Fund or State Lottery Fund revenues appropriated to the director
36 for the purposes described in ORS 406.450 for the same period of time.
37 SECTION 7. Not later than January 2, 2030, the Department of Veterans’ Affairs shall
38 prepare and submit a report to the interim committees of the Legislative Assembly related
39 to veterans and the Association of Oregon Counties on the distribution of moneys under the
40 process provided by the amendments to ORS 406.462 by section 6 of this 2026 Act.
