26 VETERAN EDUCATIONAL BRIDGE GRANT PROGRAM
27
28 SECTION 10. ORS 408.115 is amended to read:
29 408.115. (1) The Veteran Educational Bridge Grant Program is established within the Depart-
30 ment of Veterans’ Affairs. Under the program, the department shall conduct outreach and provide
31 grants to veterans who:
32 (a) Are pursuing and enrolled in a course of study that is in or part of:
33 (A) Any program for which United States Department of Veterans Affairs education benefits
34 may be used;
35 (B) A career school licensed under ORS 345.010 to 345.340;
36 (C) An apprenticeship program that is registered with the State Apprenticeship and Training
37 Council; or
38 (D) An on-the-job training program offered by a public employer;
39 [(b)(A) Are eligible to receive federal, state or other financial assistance based on prior service in
40 the Armed Forces of the United States; or]
41 [(B) Demonstrate a need for student financial aid from any federal or state assistance program,
42 including Title IV of the Higher Education Act of 1965;]
43 [(c)(A)] (b)(A) Are unable to complete a degree, apprenticeship or training program within the
44 expected completion period because one or more required courses or apprenticeship or training
45 hours are not available until a later date; [or]
[4]

B-Eng. HB 4132
1 (B) Have debt on a student account due to an overpayment of federal or state tuition benefits
2 or prior course withdrawal that prevents enrollment in a future term; [and] or
3 (C) Are experiencing an instance of financial hardship that is interfering with or could
4 endanger the ability to remain enrolled in a degree, apprenticeship or training program; and
5 [(d)] (c) Are making satisfactory academic or training progress [or progress] in a program de-
6 scribed in paragraph (a) of this subsection.
7 (2) Grants under the program:
8 (a) May not exceed [$5,000] $10,000 per veteran; and
9 (b) May be made only when there are sufficient moneys in the Veteran Educational Bridge
10 Grant Program Fund established under ORS 408.125 to make the grants.
11 (3) The Department of Veterans’ Affairs shall adopt rules for the implementation and operation
12 of the program, including eligibility requirements for grant applicants.
13 (4) As used in this section, “veteran” has the meaning given that term in ORS 408.225 and in-
14 cludes disabled veterans, as defined in ORS 408.225.
15
16 VETERANS’ TREATMENT COURT
17
18 SECTION 11. (1) As used in this section:
19 (a) “Service member” means a person who is a member of the Armed Forces of the
20 United States, the reserve components of the Armed Forces of the United States or the
21 National Guard.
22 (b) “Veteran” means a person who:
23 (A) Served as a member of the Armed Forces of the United States, the reserve compo-
24 nents of the Armed Forces of the United States or the National Guard; and
25 (B) Received an honorable discharge, a general discharge under honorable conditions or
26 a discharge under other than honorable conditions.
27 (c) “Veterans’ treatment court” means a treatment drug court program, as defined in
28 ORS 3.450, that serves service members and veterans.
29 (2) The Judicial Department, in consultation with the Oregon Criminal Justice Commis-
30 sion, shall study methods for providing access to veterans’ treatment courts to the residents
31 of each county or judicial district. The study must include the identification and recommen-
32 dation of innovative, cost-efficient and data-driven means to extend the availability of
33 veterans’ treatment courts that are consistent with applicable standards developed under
34 ORS 137.680. The commission shall assist the department in conducting the study.
35 (3) In conducting the study and developing recommendations, the department and the
36 commission may consult with stakeholders and entities that engage with veterans’ treatment
37 courts.
38 (4) The department shall submit a report on its findings in the manner provided by ORS
39 192.245, and may include recommendations for legislation, to the interim committees of the
40 Legislative Assembly related to the military and veterans no later than November 1, 2026.
41 SECTION 12. Section 11 of this 2026 Act is repealed on January 2, 2027.
42
